Environmental Resource Consumption and Service Demand in Melbourne¶

Authored by: Mengkheang Neak

Duration: 90 mins
Level: Intermediate
Pre-requisite Skills: Python, Data Analysis, Visualization, Temporal Analysis, Correlation Analysis

Scenario¶

I am tasked with analyzing customer service request trends and their relationship with resource consumption and planned capital works in the City of Melbourne. The goal is to uncover operational inefficiencies, identify patterns in resource consumption, and evaluate environmental impacts to optimize city management practices. By aligning service operations with sustainable resource use, this analysis aims to provide actionable recommendations for improving service delivery, resource allocation, and environmental sustainability.

What This Use Case Will Teach You¶

At the end of this use case, you will:

  • Understand how to clean and preprocess datasets for service requests and resource consumption.
  • Perform exploratory data analysis (EDA) to extract trends and seasonal insights.
  • Identify correlations between service requests, resource consumption, and emissions.
  • Conduct seasonal and temporal trend analysis to uncover operational patterns.
  • Investigate anomalies in resource usage and emissions.
  • Develop actionable insights and recommendations for optimizing urban management practices.
  • Create a data-driven framework for aligning resource allocation with service demand.

Background and Introduction¶

Environmental sustainability is a critical focus for the City of Melbourne, particularly in aligning service delivery with efficient resource consumption. This project investigates the patterns and correlations between customer service requests, environmental resource consumption, and planned capital works, with a view toward improving operational efficiency and environmental sustainability.

By analyzing these datasets, this use case highlights key areas for improvement, identifies misalignments in resource usage, and provides data-driven recommendations to enhance city operations. Seasonal and temporal patterns are explored to optimize resource allocation and reduce the city's environmental footprint.

Datasets Used¶

  1. Customer Service Requests with Resolution Time: Includes details on service categories, resolution timelines, and geographic data for various customer service requests in Melbourne.
  2. Environmental Resources Consumed: Contains data on electricity, fuel, chemicals, air travel, and their corresponding greenhouse gas emissions.
  3. Planned Capital Works and Maintenance: Provides information on infrastructure projects, funding sources, and project details.

These datasets are sourced from public data provided by the City of Melbourne.

Implementation¶

Step 1: Data Cleaning and Preprocessing¶

  • Load and inspect the datasets.
  • Clean and preprocess the data to handle missing or inconsistent values.
  • Integrate datasets to establish a unified analysis framework.

Step 2: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • Generate summary statistics for key metrics, including service requests, resource usage, and emissions.
  • Analyze service categories and their geographic distribution.
  • Visualize patterns in resource consumption and emissions over time.

Step 3: Temporal and Seasonal Analysis¶

  • Identify seasonal trends in service requests and resource consumption.
  • Analyze the correlation between service demand and resource usage.
  • Investigate anomalies, such as the resource spikes observed in July 2013.

Step 4: Cross-Analysis of Service Requests and Resource Usage¶

  • Compare seasonal trends in service demand with resource consumption.
  • Evaluate the alignment between high-demand periods and resource-intensive activities.
  • Quantify correlations between requests, resource usage, and emissions.

Step 5: Investigation of Resource Anomalies¶

  • Focus on resource and emission spikes in July 2013 and other anomalous periods.
  • Investigate potential causes such as large-scale infrastructure projects or special events.
  • Cross-reference resource patterns with planned capital works data.

Step 6: Strategic Recommendations¶

  • Provide actionable insights to optimize resource allocation based on seasonal service demand.
  • Suggest operational changes to align resource consumption with service delivery.
  • Develop sustainability-focused strategies to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.

Conclusion¶

By following this use case, you will:

  • Gain a detailed understanding of the relationship between service delivery and environmental sustainability.
  • Identify inefficiencies in resource allocation and service demand alignment.
  • Provide data-driven recommendations for improving urban management practices.
  • Contribute to Melbourne’s goals for operational efficiency and environmental sustainability.

The actionable insights derived from this analysis will empower the City of Melbourne to align service delivery with sustainable resource use, contributing to a more livable and environmentally friendly city.

def API_Unlimited(datasetname): # pass in dataset name and api key
    dataset_id = datasetname

    base_url = 'https://data.melbourne.vic.gov.au/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/'
    #apikey = api_key
    dataset_id = dataset_id
    format = 'csv'

    url = f'{base_url}{dataset_id}/exports/{format}'
    params = {
        'select': '*',
        'limit': -1,  # all records
        'lang': 'en',
        'timezone': 'UTC'
    }

    # GET request
    response = requests.get(url, params=params)

    if response.status_code == 200:
        # StringIO to read the CSV data
        url_content = response.content.decode('utf-8')
        datasetname = pd.read_csv(StringIO(url_content), delimiter=';')
        print(datasetname.sample(10, random_state=999)) # Test
        return datasetname 
    else:
        return (print(f'Request failed with status code {response.status_code}'))

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing¶

To ensure the datasets were properly prepared for analysis, a detailed data cleaning process was conducted. The primary focus was on addressing inconsistencies, handling missing data, and standardizing the structure for effective analysis.

Key Cleaning Actions¶

  1. Duplicate Removal:

    • Checked for and eliminated duplicate rows to avoid redundant information in all datasets.

  2. Irrelevant Columns Dropped:

    • Columns that were either not useful for the analysis or contained all missing values were removed to simplify the datasets.

  3. Missing Values Addressed:

    • For the Customer Service Requests dataset, rows with missing data were dropped to ensure accuracy in service resolution patterns.
    • For the Environmental Resources dataset, missing numeric values (e.g., amount, total_greenhouse_gases_(t_co2-e)) were replaced with 0 to avoid skewing results.
    • For the Planned Capital Works dataset, categorical missing values (e.g., description) were replaced with "Unknown" for consistency.

  4. Standardized Column Names and Data Types:

    • Column headers across all datasets were renamed to lowercase, replacing spaces with underscores for uniformity.
    • Date columns (e.g., date_received, billing_start_date) were converted to the datetime format to enable seamless temporal analysis.

Results of Cleaning¶

Customer Service Requests Dataset:¶

  • Final dataset contains 21,310 entries with all key metrics cleaned and ready for analysis.
  • Examples of key fields:
    • category (e.g., Waste Management, Graffiti),
    • days_to_complete (resolution time in days), and
    • suburb (geographical focus).

Environmental Resources Dataset:¶

  • Cleaned to 9,474 entries with numeric values for resource consumption and emissions filled accurately.
  • Fields like amount and total_greenhouse_gases_(t_co2-e) are now ready for correlation and temporal analysis.

Planned Capital Works Dataset:¶

  • Reduced to 133 entries, ensuring financial and project descriptions are properly formatted.
  • Includes details like expenditure_type, program, and total_funding, providing insights into infrastructure investments.

Prepared for Analysis¶

After cleaning, all datasets are ready for in-depth analyses, including:

  • Exploring seasonal trends in service requests.
  • Analyzing environmental impacts of resource usage.
  • Evaluating correlations between service demands, resource consumption, and planned infrastructure spending.

This structured data preparation ensures accurate and actionable insights in the subsequent analysis stages.

Data Analysis (EDA)¶

Description¶

This step provides a comprehensive analysis of the cleaned datasets through summary statistics and visualizations. The goal is to understand key trends, distributions, and data characteristics to set the stage for deeper analysis.

Key Activities¶

  1. Descriptive Statistics:

    • Purpose: To understand central tendencies, variability, and overall data distributions.
    • Output:
      • For the Customer Service Requests dataset, statistics such as mean, median, standard deviation, and range of days_to_complete provide insights into service resolution times.
      • For the Environmental Resources dataset, descriptive statistics on amount and total_greenhouse_gases_(t_co2-e) reveal trends in resource consumption and emissions.
      • For the Planned Capital Works dataset, metrics like cash, grants, and total_funding offer insights into financial allocations.

  2. Histograms:

    • Purpose: To visualize the frequency distribution of key numerical variables.
    • Columns Visualized:
      • Customer Service Requests: days_to_complete (time taken to resolve service requests).
      • Environmental Resources: Distribution of resource consumption (amount) over time.
    • Output:
      • Histograms show the spread and skewness of resolution times and resource usage.
      • For example, a right-skewed histogram for days_to_complete indicates that most requests are resolved quickly, with a few taking significantly longer.

  3. Time-Series Line Plots:

    • Purpose: To observe trends over time in resource consumption and service requests.
    • Columns Visualized:
      • Environmental Resources: Resource consumption (amount) and greenhouse gas emissions over billing periods.
    • Output:
      • Time-series plots reveal peaks and troughs in resource usage, highlighting high-demand periods.

  4. Count Plots:

    • Purpose: To identify the distribution of planned projects by funding sources.
    • Columns Visualized:
      • Planned Capital Works dataset: Count of projects by funding sources (if available).
    • Output:
      • Bar plots show the relative distribution of projects based on funding, identifying key funding sources.

Output Analysis¶

  1. Customer Service Requests Dataset:

    • The average resolution time is approximately 10.5 days, with a standard deviation of 18 days, indicating significant variability in service completion times.
    • A histogram of days_to_complete reveals that most requests are resolved within a week, with occasional long-resolution outliers.

  2. Environmental Resources Dataset:

    • The dataset highlights substantial variability in resource usage, with peaks in certain periods driven by specific resource categories.
    • Descriptive statistics for total_greenhouse_gases_(t_co2-e) reveal notable emissions spikes, useful for identifying operational inefficiencies.

  3. Planned Capital Works Dataset:

    • Financial data indicates significant investment in property and building improvements.
    • Count plots highlight the dominance of specific funding sources in project allocation, aiding prioritization and decision-making.

Visual Summary¶

  • Histograms:

    • Display the distribution of numerical variables, revealing patterns like skewness in service resolution times or clustering of low resource usage.

  • Line Plots:

    • Show temporal trends in resource consumption and emissions, helping to identify peak-demand periods.

  • Bar Plots:

    • Highlight the distribution of planned works by funding source, providing insights into resource allocation strategies.

Conclusion¶

This exploratory analysis provides a strong foundation for deeper investigations. The visualizations and statistics highlight key areas for further exploration:

  • Analyzing correlations between resource usage and service trends.
  • Investigating peaks in resource usage and emissions.
  • Evaluating funding distribution patterns and their alignment with service demands.

The insights gained from EDA ensure the datasets are ready for advanced analysis and decision-making.

# Visualize total resource consumption over time (check if 'date' and 'total_consumption' columns exist)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
if 'date' in environmental_resources_df.columns and 'total_consumption' in environmental_resources_df.columns:
    sns.lineplot(data=environmental_resources_df, x='date', y='total_consumption')
    plt.title('Total Environmental Resource Consumption Over Time')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Total Consumption')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.show()

    print("Columns 'date' or 'total_consumption' not found in Environmental Resources dataset.")

print("Planned Capital Works - Basic Info:")

print("Planned Capital Works - Statistical Summary:")

# Visualize number of planned works by funding source (check if 'funding_source' column exists)
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
if 'funding_source' in capital_works_df.columns:
    sns.countplot(data=capital_works_df, x='funding_source')
    plt.title('Number of Planned Works by Funding Source')
    plt.xlabel('Funding Source')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Projects')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.show()
else:
    print("Column 'funding_source' not found in Capital Works dataset.")

Seasonal Trend Analysis of Customer Service Requests¶

Objective¶

The goal of this analysis was to examine the monthly trends in customer service requests to uncover seasonal patterns. By visualizing the distribution of service requests over time, we can identify periods of increased demand, helping to optimize resource allocation and service planning.

Methodology¶

  1. Data Preparation:

    • The date_received column in the Customer Service Requests dataset was converted to a datetime format.
    • Year and month were extracted from the date_received column to enable grouping by time periods.

  2. Grouping and Aggregation:

    • The data was grouped by year and month to calculate the total number of service requests for each period.
    • The resulting dataset provides the total request count for each month, enabling a clear view of seasonal trends.

  3. Visualization:

    • A line plot was created to display the number of requests over time, with markers highlighting monthly data points.
    • The x-axis represents the year-month combination, while the y-axis indicates the number of requests.

Key Findings¶

  • Overall Trend:

    • The number of service requests showed a steady increase from late 2014 to mid-2016, indicating growing service demand during this period.
    • There is a notable drop in requests towards the end of 2016, possibly due to incomplete data for November or operational shifts.

  • Seasonal Patterns:

    • Peaks in service requests occur consistently around the summer months (e.g., December and January), suggesting higher demand during warmer periods.
    • Dips in demand are evident in the mid-year periods (e.g., June and July), potentially aligning with colder weather and reduced outdoor activities.

Output Analysis¶

  1. Seasonal Insights:

    • The seasonal trend reveals predictable demand cycles, with higher activity in warmer months.
    • These findings suggest a link between seasonal factors and service request volumes, which can inform staffing and resource deployment strategies.

  2. Potential Anomalies:

    • The sharp decline in late 2016 requests warrants further investigation to determine if it reflects actual trends or data issues.

Conclusion¶

This seasonal trend analysis highlights the cyclical nature of customer service demands, providing valuable insights for operational planning:

  • Summer Peaks: Allocate additional resources to handle increased requests.
  • Winter Lows: Optimize resource utilization during off-peak periods.
  • Long-Term Planning: Use these insights to forecast demand and enhance service efficiency.

The next step is to investigate specific categories driving these trends and correlate them with environmental and operational factors to refine recommendations.

Correlation Analysis: Service Requests vs Environmental Resource Consumption¶

Objective¶

The objective of this analysis is to explore the relationship between the volume of service requests and environmental resource usage over time. This helps in identifying whether resource-intensive operations align with fluctuations in service demand, thereby uncovering potential inefficiencies or trends.

Methodology¶

  1. Data Integration:

    • The Customer Service Requests dataset was merged with the Environmental Resources Consumed dataset using an outer join to ensure all time periods are included, even those with no overlaps.
    • Missing values were replaced with 0 to account for periods with no recorded data.

  2. Time Alignment:

    • A unified time column was created by combining year and month, enabling consistent temporal analysis.

  3. Trend Analysis:

    • Time series plots were generated to visualize trends in service requests, resource usage, and greenhouse gas emissions.
    • Key metrics analyzed:
      • Request Count (volume of customer service requests)
      • Resource Amount (total environmental resources consumed)
      • Greenhouse Gases (CO2-equivalent emissions)

  4. Correlation Analysis:

    • A correlation matrix was computed to examine the strength of relationships between:
      • Service Requests
      • Resource Consumption
      • Greenhouse Gas Emissions

Key Findings¶

Time Series Trends¶

  • Service Requests:

    • Service requests exhibit a relatively stable trend with small fluctuations over time.
    • Peaks are not strongly aligned with resource usage spikes.

  • Resource Consumption:

    • Resource consumption exhibits a significant spike in mid-2013, likely driven by specific operational demands or projects.

  • Greenhouse Gas Emissions:

    • CO2-equivalent emissions follow a trend similar to resource usage, indicating a direct link between resource intensity and environmental impact.

Correlation Insights¶

  • Request Count vs Resource Amount:

    • A moderate negative correlation (-0.45), suggesting that periods of high resource consumption do not necessarily correspond to higher service demand.

  • Request Count vs Greenhouse Gases:

    • A slightly stronger negative correlation (-0.53), highlighting that resource-intensive operations may not be directly tied to customer service trends.

  • Resource Amount vs Greenhouse Gases:

    • A very strong positive correlation (0.96), confirming that resource consumption directly drives greenhouse gas emissions.

Output Analysis¶

  1. Insights from Trends:

    • Resource usage spikes in mid-2013 are not reflected in service request volumes, implying that resource-heavy operations might be independent of customer service activities.
    • Service requests are more consistent over time, showing minor seasonal variations.

  2. Environmental Implications:

    • Significant spikes in greenhouse gas emissions align with resource usage peaks, highlighting the environmental costs of operational activities.

  3. Potential Operational Gaps:

    • The lack of alignment between resource consumption and service requests suggests opportunities to optimize resource allocation and reduce environmental impact.

Conclusion¶

This analysis underscores the need for:

  • Operational Optimization: Aligning resource consumption with periods of high service demand to ensure efficient resource utilization.
  • Sustainability Measures: Reducing resource usage and emissions during periods of low service demand to enhance sustainability.
  • Future Focus: Investigating specific drivers of resource and emission spikes, such as large-scale projects or operational inefficiencies, to mitigate their environmental footprint.

These findings provide actionable insights for balancing operational efficiency and environmental sustainability.

Seasonal Analysis of Top Service Request Categories¶

Objective¶

The goal of this analysis is to identify seasonal trends in customer service requests for the top two service categories: Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter and Graffiti. This analysis provides insights into how the demand for these services fluctuates throughout the year, enabling targeted resource planning and operational efficiency.

Methodology¶

  1. Data Filtering:

    • The dataset was filtered to include only the top two service request categories: Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter and Graffiti.
    • For each request, the month of occurrence was extracted to analyze seasonal patterns.

  2. Grouping:

    • Requests were grouped by category and month to calculate the total number of requests for each category in each month across all years.

  3. Visualization:

    • A line plot was used to represent the monthly trends for each category, highlighting seasonal peaks and troughs.

Key Findings¶

Seasonal Trends¶

  1. Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter:

    • This category experiences consistently high request volumes throughout the year, with slight increases during the warmer months (June to August).
    • A noticeable dip occurs in November and December, likely corresponding to holiday periods.

  2. Graffiti:

    • Graffiti requests show a clear seasonal pattern, peaking in the summer months (January to March) and declining in the colder months (October to December).
    • The demand for graffiti-related services is lower compared to waste and litter services but displays more pronounced seasonal variation.

Insights and Recommendations¶

  1. Operational Efficiency:

    • Allocate additional resources for Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter during the summer months to handle increased demand.
    • Reduce resource allocation in November and December when demand declines.

  2. Graffiti Management:

    • Intensify graffiti prevention and removal efforts during the peak season (January to March) to address higher demand.
    • Focus on proactive strategies, such as public awareness campaigns, during the off-season.

  3. Seasonal Planning:

    • Develop seasonally adjusted operational schedules to align with the observed demand patterns, ensuring efficient resource utilization.

Conclusion¶

This seasonal analysis highlights distinct patterns in customer service demands for top service categories. By aligning resource planning and operational efforts with these trends, the City of Melbourne can enhance service delivery, optimize costs, and improve urban management.

Suburb Analysis of Service Requests¶

Objective¶

The aim of this analysis is to identify the top suburbs generating the highest number of service requests for the two leading categories: Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter and Graffiti. This insight is crucial for understanding localized demand patterns and optimizing resource allocation for these services.

Methodology¶

  1. Data Filtering:

    • The dataset was filtered to include only the top two categories: Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter and Graffiti.
    • Suburbs were grouped by category to calculate the total number of requests for each suburb.

  2. Top Suburb Identification:

    • For each category, the top 10 suburbs with the highest total requests were identified and sorted.

  3. Visualization:

    • Bar plots were created to visualize the distribution of total requests across the top 10 suburbs for each category.
    • Additionally, a heatmap was generated to provide a comprehensive view of service demand across suburbs and categories.

Key Findings¶

Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter¶

  • Top Suburb: Melbourne
  • Other prominent suburbs include North Melbourne, Carlton, and Kensington.
  • Suburbs like West Melbourne and Docklands also generate significant requests, indicating widespread demand across various city regions.

Graffiti¶

  • Top Suburb: Melbourne
  • Suburbs like Carlton, North Melbourne, and Kensington show high graffiti service demand, consistent with urban areas prone to graffiti incidents.
  • Suburbs with lower requests include Southbank and South Yarra, suggesting less graffiti activity in these areas.

Insights and Recommendations¶

  1. Localized Resource Allocation:

    • For Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter, deploy additional cleaning resources to Melbourne, North Melbourne, and Carlton to handle peak demand.
    • For Graffiti, focus on proactive graffiti removal measures in Melbourne and Carlton, where incidents are most frequent.

  2. Suburb-Specific Strategies:

    • Tailor cleaning schedules to align with the peak demand periods observed in top suburbs for Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter.
    • Implement community awareness campaigns in high-demand graffiti suburbs to prevent graffiti incidents.

  3. Heatmap Insights:

    • The heatmap revealed spatial clustering of demand, particularly in Melbourne and surrounding suburbs, underscoring the need for a centralized but adaptable operational approach.

Conclusion¶

The suburb-level analysis of service requests highlights significant geographic variations in demand for the top two categories. This insight allows for targeted resource planning and operational efficiency improvements, enhancing service delivery in high-demand suburbs.

Temporal Analysis of Suburb Trends¶

Objective¶

The objective of this analysis is to explore the temporal dynamics of service requests across the top suburbs for Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter and Graffiti categories. This provides insight into how demand patterns evolve over time, enabling better planning and resource allocation.

Methodology¶

  1. Suburb Selection:

    • The top 10 suburbs for each category were identified from the previous suburb analysis.
    • These suburbs were filtered for temporal trend analysis.

  2. Data Transformation:

    • The date_received column was converted into a year_month period format to group requests by month and year.
    • Total requests were calculated for each suburb-category combination on a monthly basis.

  3. Visualization:

    • Separate line plots were generated for each category, showing monthly trends for the top suburbs.

Key Findings¶

Waste, Street Cleaning and Litter¶

  • Melbourne consistently exhibited the highest volume of requests across all months, with peaks in mid-2015 and mid-2016.
  • Other suburbs like North Melbourne and Carlton displayed steady but lower demand trends, with occasional spikes during seasonal transitions (e.g., summer months).
  • Docklands and Parkville, though less active, exhibited localized surges in specific months, likely due to one-time events or seasonal factors.

Graffiti¶

  • Melbourne and Carlton showed the highest and most consistent demand, particularly during the first half of 2016.
  • Suburbs like North Melbourne and Kensington also demonstrated upward trends in graffiti-related requests, peaking in early 2016.
  • Declines were observed in most suburbs toward the end of 2016, potentially indicating effective mitigation measures or seasonal trends.

Insights and Recommendations¶

  1. Temporal Peaks:

    • The data reveals clear temporal spikes in requests for both categories, with mid-year peaks (June-July) for waste and graffiti services. This aligns with increased activities or waste generation during this period.
    • Plan for additional staffing and resource allocation during these peak months.

  2. Suburb-Specific Trends:

    • Focus on Melbourne, Carlton, and North Melbourne for graffiti-related issues, especially during the first half of the year.
    • Target Docklands and Parkville during specific months when spikes occur, as these areas have irregular but notable demand surges.

  3. Operational Strategies:

    • Implement proactive cleaning and graffiti removal campaigns before the anticipated mid-year peaks.
    • Coordinate efforts with planned events or seasonal activities to ensure adequate service coverage.

Conclusion¶

Temporal trends provide valuable insights into the evolution of service demand across suburbs. This analysis highlights the importance of dynamic resource planning and targeted interventions to maintain service efficiency during high-demand periods.

Temporal Trends: Service Requests vs Resource Consumption¶

Objective¶

To analyze the relationship between service requests and resource consumption, identifying temporal patterns and correlations that can inform operational efficiencies and environmental sustainability strategies.

Methodology¶

  1. Data Preparation:

    • Aggregated total service requests monthly across all suburbs and categories.
    • Summed resource consumption metrics (e.g., amount of resources consumed and greenhouse gas emissions) by month and year.
    • Merged the two datasets on a year_month basis using an outer join to ensure inclusion of all time periods.

  2. Analysis Steps:

    • Filled missing values with zeros for consistency in the analysis.
    • Generated summary statistics for resource consumption and emissions.
    • Computed a correlation matrix to quantify the relationship between service requests, resource consumption, and emissions.
    • Visualized the trends and correlations using line plots and heatmaps.

Key Findings¶

Merged Dataset Insights¶

  • The dataset spans multiple years, providing a comprehensive view of both service demand and environmental impacts.
  • Resource Consumption:
    • Average resource usage per month: ~1.47 million units.
    • Peak usage in July 2013, with 20.67 million units consumed.
  • Greenhouse Gas Emissions:
    • Average emissions per month: ~0.98 million CO2-e units.
    • Highest emissions observed in July 2013, correlating with peak resource usage.
  • Service Requests:
    • Service request trends were generally steady but showed periodic spikes, particularly in late 2015 and early 2016.

Correlation Analysis¶

  • Service Requests vs Resource Usage:
    • Correlation coefficient: -0.44 (weak negative correlation).
    • Suggests that periods of high resource consumption do not align with periods of high service requests.
  • Resource Usage vs Greenhouse Gas Emissions:
    • Correlation coefficient: 0.96 (strong positive correlation).
    • Indicates that resource usage is a significant driver of greenhouse gas emissions.
  • Service Requests vs Emissions:
    • Correlation coefficient: -0.52 (weak negative correlation).
    • Implies minimal direct alignment between service activity and emissions.

Visualizations¶

1. Correlation Matrix¶

The heatmap visually depicts the correlations:

  • Strong alignment between resource consumption and emissions.
  • Weak inverse relationships between service requests and environmental metrics.

2. Temporal Trends¶

  • Resource Usage and Emissions:
    • Dramatic peaks in mid-2013, tapering off afterward.
    • Seasonal fluctuations evident, with spikes aligning to mid-year months (July-August).
  • Service Requests:
    • Moderate upward trend with periodic peaks, unrelated to resource consumption.

Insights and Recommendations¶

  1. Resource Optimization:

    • High resource usage and emissions in mid-2013 warrant further investigation to identify inefficiencies or extraordinary events.
    • Implement energy-efficient practices and monitor high-emission periods for intervention opportunities.

  2. Decoupling Service Demand and Resources:

    • The weak correlation suggests an opportunity to optimize service delivery without increasing environmental costs.
    • Develop predictive models to align resources with service demand more effectively.

  3. Seasonal Planning:

    • Leverage insights into mid-year peaks in resource usage and emissions to schedule preventive measures and resource audits.

Conclusion¶

This analysis highlights the interplay between operational activities and environmental impact, underscoring the need for sustainable resource management. Strategic interventions can optimize resource allocation while maintaining service quality and reducing environmental footprints.

Seasonal Trends in Resource Usage and Emissions¶

Objective¶

To analyze seasonal patterns in resource usage and emissions across the year, identifying months with peak activities and their environmental impact.

Methodology¶

  1. Data Preparation:

    • Extracted the month from the year_month column in the merged dataset containing both service request and resource consumption data.
    • Grouped the data by month to calculate average resource usage and average emissions across all years.

  2. Analysis:

    • Computed monthly averages for:
      • Resource Amount: Quantifying the volume of resources consumed.
      • Emissions (tCO2-e): Measuring greenhouse gas emissions resulting from resource usage.
    • Visualized trends using a line plot to identify peaks and seasonal fluctuations.

Findings¶

Seasonal Analysis Summary¶

  • Highest Resource Usage:
    • July emerges as the peak month for resource consumption, with an average usage significantly higher than other months.
    • Suggests increased operational or energy demands during mid-year.
  • Highest Emissions:
    • July also has the highest average greenhouse gas emissions, directly correlating with resource usage.
  • Lower Activity Periods:
    • February and October show the lowest averages for both metrics, indicating reduced activity or higher efficiency.

Visualizations¶

1. Seasonal Trends¶

  • A line plot illustrates monthly averages for both resource usage and emissions:
    • Sharp Peak in July: Highlights the need for focused resource efficiency strategies during this period.
    • Similar Trends: Resource usage and emissions closely align across all months, confirming the direct relationship between the two.

Actionable Insights¶

  1. Peak Month Management (July):

    • Investigate the operational drivers of resource consumption during July.
    • Implement targeted energy-saving initiatives or resource audits in preparation for mid-year peaks.

  2. Year-Round Efficiency:

    • Focus on maintaining low-consumption months (e.g., February and October) as benchmarks for efficiency across the year.
    • Explore whether similar strategies can be applied to higher-consumption months.

  3. Sustainability Planning:

    • Prioritize mid-year months for sustainability programs, including offsetting greenhouse gas emissions.
    • Align these initiatives with organizational activities or seasonal demand spikes.

Conclusion¶

This seasonal analysis reveals clear trends in resource usage and environmental impact, with significant implications for operational planning and sustainability. Addressing mid-year peaks can improve efficiency and reduce environmental costs while maintaining service quality.

Seasonal Cross-Analysis: Service Requests, Resource Usage, and Emissions¶

Objective¶

To identify and analyze the relationship between seasonal service requests, resource usage, and greenhouse gas emissions, exploring alignment in their patterns and uncovering potential operational drivers.

Methodology¶

  1. Data Preparation:

    • Extracted month from the year_month column to align seasonal trends for service requests, resource consumption, and emissions.
    • Grouped data by month to calculate:
      • Average Service Requests: Seasonal demand for city services.
      • Average Resource Usage: Consumption of operational resources.
      • Average Emissions (tCO2-e): Environmental impact of resource consumption.

  2. Merged Seasonal Trends:

    • Combined the seasonal datasets for cross-analysis, enabling the identification of shared patterns across requests, resource usage, and emissions.

  3. Correlation Analysis:

    • Calculated the correlation matrix to measure the strength of relationships between service requests, resource usage, and emissions.

Findings¶

Seasonal Cross-Analysis Summary¶

  • Service Requests:

    • Peak demand occurs in May and July, aligning with operational activity spikes.
    • Lowest activity is observed in November, reflecting potential periods of reduced service demand.

  • Resource Usage and Emissions:

    • Resource consumption and emissions show clear alignment, peaking in July, confirming a strong operational correlation.
    • November also exhibits the lowest resource usage and emissions, in line with reduced service activity.

  • Shared Peaks:

    • July stands out as a critical month where service requests, resource consumption, and emissions converge, indicating a period of high operational and environmental intensity.

Visualizations¶

1. Seasonal Trends¶

  • The line plot illustrates monthly averages for:
    • Service Requests: Blue dotted line.
    • Resource Usage: Solid blue line.
    • Emissions: Dashed orange line.
  • Findings from Visuals:
    • Resource usage and emissions follow a nearly identical seasonal pattern, reinforcing their direct relationship.
    • Service requests peak at slightly different times but show a clear operational dependency.

2. Correlation Matrix¶

  • Key Correlations:
    • Service Requests vs Resource Usage: Positive correlation (0.44), indicating that higher service demand drives resource consumption.
    • Service Requests vs Emissions: Moderate positive correlation (0.51), suggesting that increased operational activity impacts emissions.
    • Resource Usage vs Emissions: Strong positive correlation (0.99), reflecting a direct relationship.

Actionable Insights¶

  1. Operational Optimization:

    • Investigate drivers of July's resource-intensive operations to identify efficiency opportunities.
    • Consider resource redistribution during high-demand periods like May and July.

  2. Sustainability Initiatives:

    • Target emission reductions during peak months by adopting greener resource strategies (e.g., renewable energy sources).
    • Develop programs to offset emissions, particularly in July when both resource usage and emissions peak.

  3. Demand-Driven Resource Planning:

    • Utilize historical request patterns to proactively allocate resources during high-demand months.
    • Leverage November's lower service demand for maintenance and sustainability projects.

Conclusion¶

This cross-analysis highlights a seasonal alignment between service requests, resource usage, and emissions. The findings underscore the importance of addressing peak months like July with targeted operational and environmental strategies, ensuring sustainable and efficient city management.

Environmental and Operational Analysis of Service Requests in Melbourne¶

Strategic Findings¶

1. Baseline Insights¶

  • Service Requests: Seasonal trends in service requests revealed peak activity in July and May, with the lowest levels in November. This reflects an operational dependency on specific months with potential causes tied to city events or environmental factors.
  • Resource Usage and Emissions: Resource consumption and greenhouse gas emissions strongly align, with July being the most resource-intensive month. This month exhibited a 2x spike in resource usage and emissions, driven by high service demand and operational intensity.
  • Correlation Analysis:
    • A moderate positive correlation (0.44) exists between service requests and resource usage, suggesting operational demand drives consumption.
    • A strong correlation (0.99) between resource usage and emissions confirms a direct link between operational activity and environmental impact.

2. Suburb-Level Insights¶

  • Waste, Street Cleaning, and Litter:

    • Melbourne CBD, North Melbourne, and Carlton are the highest-demand areas for waste management services, accounting for the majority of service requests.
    • Seasonal trends show consistent demand across the year, with minor peaks during mid-year.

  • Graffiti Removal:

    • Melbourne CBD and Carlton lead in graffiti-related requests, reflecting their dense urban activity.
    • Graffiti-related demand peaks during warmer months, likely tied to outdoor activity and events.

3. Seasonal Resource and Service Alignment¶

  • Shared Peaks:

    • High service requests and resource consumption converge in July, signaling a critical month for optimizing operations and sustainability.
    • Alignment between high service requests and resource usage underscores a need for pre-emptive resource allocation during peak months.

  • Distinct Trends:

    • Service requests, while aligning with resource usage in some months, deviate during off-peak periods. This suggests inefficiencies or potential opportunities for resource redistribution.

4. Strategic Opportunities¶

  • Operational Efficiency:

    • Redistribute resources during off-peak months (e.g., November) for maintenance and sustainability initiatives.
    • Develop proactive resource allocation plans for high-demand months like May and July.

  • Environmental Impact Mitigation:

    • Implement sustainability practices to reduce emissions during high-intensity periods.
    • Explore green technologies, such as renewable energy adoption, to decouple emissions from resource consumption.

Strategic Action Plan¶

1. Peak Resource Optimization¶

Objective: Address the operational and environmental intensity of peak months (e.g., July).

Actions:

  • Resource Allocation: Increase operational readiness and allocate resources in anticipation of July’s high demand.
  • Efficiency Measures: Optimize workflows during peak months to reduce emissions without sacrificing service quality.
  • Event Forecasting: Use historical data to predict demand spikes, particularly during city-wide events.

2. Suburb-Specific Resource Planning¶

Objective: Tailor resource strategies to suburb-specific demands.

Actions:

  • High-Demand Suburbs:
    • Allocate additional resources to high-demand suburbs like Melbourne CBD, Carlton, and North Melbourne.
    • Prioritize sustainable solutions in these areas to offset their environmental burden.
  • Low-Demand Suburbs:
    • Use off-peak suburbs as testing grounds for innovative resource management strategies.

3. Sustainability Integration¶

Objective: Minimize emissions and optimize resource usage through sustainable practices.

Actions:

  • Renewable Energy: Transition to greener energy sources for resource-intensive operations.
  • Carbon Offsetting: Launch initiatives to offset emissions during peak operational periods.
  • Circular Resource Management: Implement recycling and reuse practices in waste management services.

4. Community Engagement¶

Objective: Engage Melbourne residents in sustainability and operational planning.

Actions:

  • Public Awareness Campaigns: Educate residents on the link between service demands and environmental impacts.
  • Volunteer Programs: Foster community participation in waste management and graffiti removal.
  • Feedback Mechanisms: Develop platforms for residents to report inefficiencies or propose solutions.

5. Monitoring and Continuous Improvement¶

Objective: Track and refine strategies using data-driven insights.

Actions:

  • Data Dashboards: Establish live dashboards to monitor service requests, resource consumption, and emissions in real-time.
  • Periodic Reviews: Conduct quarterly reviews of operational and environmental performance.
